        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP" source="#autopsy">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name><gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/><w part="F">ιανε</w></name></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/><supplied reason="lost">χρη</supplied><unclear>σ</unclear>τέ χαῖ
                    <lb n="3" break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">ρε</supplied> <supplied reason="lost">ἔζ</supplied>ησας
                    <lb n="4"/><gap reason="lost" unit="character" extent="unknown"/>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus" resp="#JP">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>text from autopsy</note></app>
                    <app loc="1"><note>Orsi: [Χρησ]ιανε</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Farewell, worthy [---]ianos, you lived [---(age) ---].</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#JP">
                <p>It appears that c.4-5 letters are missing on the left side of the plaque, and this is likely to have followed the fairly standard formula of such epitaphs, with potentially just a final line detailing the age in years. The name could be one of many, such as Ioulianos, Markianos, Clodianos, Loukianos, Phlabianos, etc.</p>
            </div>
